<TEXT>
about 400 people trudged in out of a 
pounding rain one recent night to hoot and holler at the citys 
favorite spectator sport 
politics 
politics is like baseball in jersey city and its hardball 
all the time said thomas mansheim chairman of the department of 
urban studies at st peters college people are interested in 
it they follow it and a lot of times their jobs are dependent on 
it so they really live for it 
this year its politics as unusual in jersey city an 
industrial waterfront city of 230000 that sits a stones throw 
from the statue of liberty on the western shore of new york harbor 
a record 10 candidates are running for mayor in tuesdays 
freeforall if no candidate receives more than 50 percent of the 
vote the top two finishers will spend another month hurling 
epithets until a june 13 runoff 
the election is nonpartisan but a registered democrat likely 
will win since democrats have outnumbered republicans as long as 
anyone can remember today the ratio is 13to1 
the lineup of candidates includes the incumbent two former 
mayors four city councilmen a banker a police officer and an 
insurance broker 
decorum is not their best quality 
lofty promises of political reform are met with sarcasm often 
sparking hearty guffaws from voters and biting attacks abound 
among the candidates 
in campaign advertisements one candidate refers to his 
opponents as political hacks another says hes fighting the 
corrupt political machine 
based on each camps estimates more than 3 million will be 
spent to capture the 65000ayear job jersey citys mayor 
influences spending of about 400 millionplus in public funds and 
has final sayso on filling approximately 6500 city jobs 
