<TEXT>
the percentage of victims of rape robbery and 
assault who were physically injured during the attack increased 
from 1979 to 1986 according to a department of justice survey 
caroline wolf harlow the statistician who prepared the report 
issued sunday said that although violent crime rates dropped about 
11 percent from 1973 to 1986 the number of injuries about 22 
million a year did not 
since injuries have remained relatively constant over the 
period a higher proportion of victims of violent crime today are 
injured she said 
the report covered only rape robbery and assault for people at 
least 12 years old it did not cover murder manslaughter and child 
abuse 
the report was based on findings of the national crime survey 
which questioned an average of 116000 respondents in 55000 
households in each year of the survey the results include crimes 
not reported to police 
because of the large percentage of people questioned each year 
compared with the total number of crime victims the results are 
not subject to the margin of error limitations of a smaller poll 
over the years 19791986 a total of about 63 million people in 
the united states were victims of rape robbery or assault of whom 
177 million were injured the report concluded 
of the average 22 million people hurt each year 357830 
suffered serious injury and 183 million suffered minor injury 
about 1 percent or almost 23000 people suffered gunshot wounds 
about 77000 had knife wounds 141500 suffered broken bones or 
teeth 64000 had internal injuries and 84000 lost consciousness 
according to the report 
the percentage of victims who were injured during the attack was 
275 percent in 1973 and remained relatively constant except for a 
drop to 269 percent in 1982 before climbing the next few years to 
303 percent in 1986 ms harlow said in an interview citing 
figures not included in the report which covered only 197986 
the actual rate of violent crime that is the number of victims 
of rape robbery or assault per 1000 people decreased 
substantially in the last few years of the survey she said 
the highest rate since 1973 was in 1981 when 456 per 1000 
were victims of such crimes that number dropped to 367 per 1000 
in 1986 but preliminary figures for 1987 and 1988 indicate the 
rate has increased again ms harlow said 
meanwhile the injury rate the number of people per 1000 who 
suffered injuries as victims of those violent crimes stayed 
relatively stable in 1973 the rate was 114 per 1000 it rose to 
a high of 127 in 1981 and then dropped to 111 in 1986 she said 
neither ms harlow nor the report she compiled gave reasons for 
the 1981 spike in crime and injury rates 
while almost half of the injured victims received some medical 
care including almost a fourth being treated in an emergency room 
or hospital one in 25 a total of about 87650 people needed to 
stay overnight in the hospital the report found 
those most likely to suffer injuries were men blacks people 
age 19 to 24 people with at most a high school education those 
who were separated or divorced poor people with family incomes 
under 10000 a year and residents of central cities 
those least likely to be injured were women whites widows 
those 50 or older people with family incomes of 30000 or more 
those who had attended college for a year or more and those who 
lived outside metropolitan areas 
